POLIOMYELITIS UPDATE (70): PAKISTAN (KHYBER PAKHTUNKHWA, SINDH)
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 26 Aug 2019
Source: Relief Web [edited]
https://reliefweb.int/report/pakistan/three-polio-cases-detected-kp-two-sindh


A total of 5 more children -- 3 from Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and 2 from Sindh -- have tested positive for poliovirus, it emerged on Sunday [25 Aug 2019].

With the latest addition, the number of polio cases in the country has climbed to 58 this year [2019], indicating a sharp increase of 383.33% from last year's [2018] figure of 12. It may be recalled that only 8 cases had been confirmed in 2017.

Of the 58 victims found this year [2019], 44 belonged to Khyber Pakhtunkhwa alone, whereas Sindh and Punjab shared 5 cases each and Balochistan reported 4 cases.

All 5 new victims are girls, and 4 of them had not received a single dose of vaccine, according to an official of [the] Polio Virology Laboratory at the National Institute of Health, Islamabad. [The] 3 cases [from] Khyber Pakhtunkhwa were reported from Bannu, Hangu and North Waziristan, while both cases [from] Sindh were reported from Hyderabad, he said while requesting anonymity.

Sharing details of the cases reported from Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, the official said: "3 girls were paralysed in KP." They included an 18-month-old resident of Hangu's tehsil Thal, a 30-month-old resident of North Waziristan's tehsil Mirali, and another 18-month-old girl from Bannu's tehsil Wazir. "All 3 had not received a single dose of polio vaccine during routine immunisation," he said.

About the cases from Hyderabad, the official said one of the girls had missed [the] polio vaccine during routine immunisation. She was a resident of Quetta Town, Hala Nakka area. The other girl, a resident of [the] Liaquat Colony area of Latifabad, had received 3 doses of polio vaccine during routine immunisation, the official confirmed. The victims were identified as a 12-month-old and a 12-year-old.

None of the victims from Khyber Pakhtunkhwa was identified.

When contacted, [the] Prime Minister's Focal Person on Polio Eradication Babar Bin Atta confirmed to Dawn that 5 more children were infected with the virus [causing the] crippling disease.

Just over 2 [weeks] ago, 5 polio cases had been confirmed from Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. So far this year [2019], 44 cases have been reported from KP, 5 each from Punjab and Sindh, while 4 cases have been reported from Balochistan. Last year [2018] when the country recorded a total of 12 polio cases, 8 of them were reported from KP.

The latest cases have been confirmed only a day before the resumption of a province-wide vaccination campaign after 4 months. Earlier during a nationwide polio campaign in April [2019], students of a school in Mashokhel were rushed to the Hayatabad Medical Complex, Peshawar, with complaints about drug reaction. However, [the] initial probe indicated that a drama had been staged to spread propaganda against polio drives, as all the children were found to be safe.

While some of the culprits were arrested and legal action was taken against them, resistance to polio vaccination has increased since then. To counter the propaganda against vaccine, the authorities have decided to launch the drive from the same village of Mashokhel.

Nearly 2 dozen [24] cases have been reported from Bannu district, followed by North Waziristan and Torghar, where at least 8 and 5 cases have been detected, respectively. Lakki Marwat and Hangu have witnessed 2 cases each this year [2019], while Shangla, Charsadda, Bajaur and Khyber districts have recorded at least one case each.

In the endemic areas, too, the government is struggling to counter the new challenge of fake markings of children by their parents amid reluctance shown against vaccination.

The province has been experiencing outbreaks since the environmental samples started testing positive in October 2018. The 1st outbreak was witnessed in Bajaur in November [2018] that lasted till January [2019]. The 2nd outbreak initially recorded in March [2019] in Bannu division is still the focus of attention.

In Torghar, the district administration will spearhead the campaign under tight security because the vaccinators are gripped by fear in the areas known for opposition to vaccination. However, the authorities claimed that elaborate arrangements had been made to run the campaign after a break of several months to ensure that all the children are administered polio drops.

Polio is a highly infectious disease caused by [a] virus mainly affecting children under the age of 5 [years]. It invades the nervous system, and can cause paralysis or even death. While there is no cure for polio, vaccination is the most effective way to protect children from the crippling disease. Each time a child aged below 5 years is vaccinated, their protection against the virus is increased. Repeated immunizations have protected millions of children from polio, allowing almost all countries, except Pakistan and Afghanistan, to become polio free.

Published in Dawn, [26 Aug 2019]
[Byline: Ikram Junaidi]

